  "prompt": "Do electrons change energy levels instantaneously?",
  "response": "No, electrons do not change energy levels instantaneously. When an electron transitions between energy levels, there are a few key points to understand:\n\n1. Quantum Leap: The transition between energy levels occurs through what's called a \"quantum leap\" or \"quantum jump.\"\n\n2. Finite Time: While extremely fast, these transitions take a finite amount of time, typically on the order of femtoseconds (10^-15 seconds).\n\n3. Photon Emission/Absorption: When an electron moves to a lower energy level, it emits a photon. When moving to a higher energy level, it absorbs a photon.\n\n4. Probability Transition: The transition follows quantum mechanical probability rules, not a classical, instantaneous path.\n\n5. Energy Conservation: The energy difference between levels is exactly equal to the energy of the emitted or absorbed photon.\n\nSo while these transitions appear nearly instantaneous from a human perspective, they are not truly instantaneous but occur over an extremely short time scale governed by quantum mechanical principles.",
